        <div>
            <h3>Testing using the Terminal</h3>
            <ol>
                <li>
                    Open the terminal or command prompt.
                    <ul>
                        <li>On Mac run the command <kbd>ping</kbd> followed by a website</li>
                        <li>One Windows run the same command <kbd>ping -t</kbd> followed by a website name. The “-t”
                            option allows ping to run until you stop. This is not needed on Mac as this is the default
                            option. </li>
                    </ul>
                </li>
                <li>Open your browser and navigate to your favorite speedtest website. If you do not know any see the
                    links below to some of my favorites.</li>
                <li>Make sure your terminal/command prompt is visible and run the speedtest.</li>
                <li>If you notice your ping start to spike significantly during your speedtest (e.g., at idle you were
                    sitting at 25 ms and during the test you were at 80 ms) then you are experiencing bufferbloat.</li>
                <li>If you experienced bufferbloat then proceed to the solution page, and if you did not experience
                    bufferbloat, do it anyway.</li>
            </ol>

            <h3>Speedtest Sites</h3>
            <ul>
                <li><a class="external-links visited" target="_blank" href="https://fast.com">Fast.com</a></li>
                <li><a class="external-links visited" target="_blank" href="https://speedtest.net">Speedtest.net</a></li>
                <li><a class="external-links visited" target="_blank" href="https://speedof.me">Speedof.me</a></li>
            </ul>

            <h3> Easier Methods </h3>
            <p>
                One of the easier methods would be to visit the fine folks at <a class="external-links" target="_blank" href="https://www.dslreports.com/speedtest?httpsok=1">dslreports.com/speedtest</a> to run the
                bufferbloat test. The best scores for bufferbloat are an A or A+. A B is acceptable, however anything
                less should prompt you to want to fix it.
            
            <br>
                Note: sometimes this test does not work well, usually because the test has met its data usage for the
                month. Also, if you are having issues with the test, try running it using http instead of https.
            <br>
        
                If the above does not sound like fun, another <em>easier</em> method (but not as easy as dsl reports)
                would be to use Netflix’s fast.com
            </p>

            <h3>Steps:</h3>
                <ol>
                    <li>Go to Fast.com</li>
                    <li>Let the first test run</li>
                    <li>After the test is done, click on “Show more info” </li>
                    <li>Click on “Settings”</li>
                    <li>Click on all three checkboxes (If your bufferbloat is down steam related 
                        then you can leave the top checkbox unchecked) </li>
                    <li>Click “Save” and let the test run again </li>
                </ol>
                <p>
                This time pay attention to your Unloaded and Loaded latencies. If you checked the 
                top box in the settings, you would see loaded latency in grey. That means it is 
                still showing you the download latency, but it will not show you the final score, 
                so, keep watching it if you are curious. Otherwise let the test run. 
                Ideally your loaded latency and unloaded latency should be equal or close to equal. 
                If loaded is significant then you have bufferbloat and proceed to the next page.
                </p>
